### Key learnings (this session)
- **LLM for perception, math for constraints**: every schema/spec failure was an unguarded LLM pick; every fix was either grounding (real values, schema meanings, upstream intent) or a structural invariant (tautology, cardinality, composite keys, leftmost convention). Guards are no-ops when the model is right — model upgrades need no code changes.
- **A saved wrong schema is worse than no schema** — it short-circuits every future ingest. Never persist junk; fail loudly.
- **The UI process caches code** — every fix needs a restart before retesting; half the "still fails" reports were stale processes.
- **LM Studio serves chat + embeddings + schema calls on one queue** — testing during ingestion starves both; schema failures mid-ingest were contention, not code.
- **Retrieval-capped counts as fallback are confidently wrong** — a failed exact count should say "couldn't determine", not return top-k as truth (future item).
- **Union of multi-file schemas is mush** — role-level machinery must scope to single-schema collections or work per source file.

